E. COLI EHEC - USA (02): (ALABAMA) O157
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 15 Apr 2022 04:51 CDT
Source: WHNT [abridged, edited]
https://whnt.com/news/northeast-alabama/adph-investigates-cases-of-e-coli-rotavirus-in-northeast-alabama/


There are cases of _E. coli_ under investigation in northeast Alabama, according to the Alabama Department of Public Health (ADPH). ADPH told News 19 the department was investigating 4 cases of _E. coli_ in young children in northeast Alabama.

The kind of _E. coli_ detected in the area is labeled O157:H7, and all people are susceptible. ADPH stressed that the most vulnerable to infection with the germ are very young children and the elderly. Those 2 groups are more likely develop severe illness and kidney issues.

ADPH said it regularly investigates clusters and outbreaks of diseases like _E. coli_.

[Byline: Zach Hester]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[Little information is given here regarding whether any complications of the infection outside the gastrointestinal tract have occurred and what is known regarding any link between the cases, as well as what vehicle for transmission is suspected. O157 is the prototypical serotype involved, but a variety of serotypes can carry the gene for the Shiga toxin that causes the illness. As many as 10% of cases may develop hemolytic uremic syndrome, which can cause kidney failure and central nervous system symptoms and may be fatal. - Mod.LL

